\par
Hamma is a well-conceived, feature-rich SSH manager. The architectural foundations are solid and the scope is impressive. But it sits firmly in "ambitious beta" territory \emdash  several blocking issues prevent a credible v1.0 release.\par
\par
Category Breakdown\par
Category\tab Score\tab Notes\par
Feature completeness\tab 7/10\tab Terminal, SFTP + editor, Docker, systemd services, packages, processes, log viewer, fleet, port forwarding, AI copilot, backup \emdash  all present and functional. Missing: SSH key generation UI, server-side alerting, fleet-level service management, no iOS/macOS parity.\par
Code quality\tab 6/10\tab Good core/features split and a clean typed exception hierarchy. Weaknesses: fragile regex-based LLM JSON extraction (\{...\} match from free-form text), main.dart is doing too much (bootstrapping + live state), ServerProfile.fromJson uses hard casts (as int, as String) without null-guards, several silent catch (_) \{\} blocks in settings/main.\par
Error handling\tab 7/10\tab SSH errors map to typed exceptions with user messages. runZonedGuarded + Sentry captures unhandled async errors. Password/key scrubbing before reporting is correct. Gap: there is no global error UI \emdash  unhandled errors are silently sent to Sentry with no recovery screen shown to the user. Settings screen swallows API key load failures entirely.\par
Security\tab 7/10\tab All credentials in flutter_secure_storage. App lock with PIN + biometrics + 5-attempt lockout. AES-256-GCM backup encryption. SSH host-key pinning. Sentry scrubbing for password/key/secret. Main gap: PBKDF2 is set to 10,000 iterations \emdash  OWASP currently recommends 600,000 for SHA-256; this is 60\'d7 too low and makes backup files brute-forceable. No certificate pinning for AI API calls.\par
Testing\tab 4.5/10\tab 195 unit tests across 19 files covering storage round-trips, SSH exception mapping, AI config, and risk assessor. Good foundation. Critical gap: zero tests for the SSH service itself (the stale-connection bug just fixed was completely untested), zero widget interaction tests, no integration tests, no golden tests. One smoke test checks the app renders \emdash  that's it for UI coverage.\par
Production infrastructure\tab 6/10\tab GitHub Actions builds all 3 platforms, tag-based releases, Sentry crash reporting. Solid for an open-source side project. Gaps: no staged rollout, no beta channel, no user-session / ANR metrics in Sentry, no Dependabot, flutter analyze only runs on Android job (not Linux/Windows).\par
Platform readiness\tab 5/10\tab Android, Linux (AppImage), Windows (installer) all build. Responsive layout works. Critical issues: CI pins Flutter 3.41.8, but Dart SDK in pubspec is ^3.7.0 \emdash  these need to be in sync. No iOS or macOS CI job at all. Background SSH keepalive on Android is fragile \emdash  OS will kill the connection. Desktop-only managers (window_manager, tray_manager) gated on platform checks \emdash  if iOS is ever added, these will need guarding at the import level.\par
Distribution / Packaging\tab 5/10\tab APK split per ABI, AppImage with correct AppRun, Inno Setup Windows installer, formatted GitHub Release body \emdash  all polished work. Showstopper: Android APKs are unsigned (can't be Play Store or reliably sideloaded). Windows installer is unsigned (Windows Defender SmartScreen will block it for every user). No Snap/Flatpak/AUR, no Play Store submission pipeline.\par
UX polish\tab 7/10\tab Custom Inter + JetBrains Mono fonts, consistent dark theme, server status indicators, AI copilot integration, onboarding carousel, proper responsive breakpoints, hidden title bar. Recent fixes (double back button, stale connection status) help. Missing: no light/dark toggle, no drag-and-drop SFTP upload, no autosave in file editor, SSH password visible as plain text in the edit form.\par
Versioning / Release strategy\tab 6/10\tab Semver tag-based releases, alpha/beta/rc pre-release detection, CHANGELOG.md present. Gap: version: 1.0.0+1 in pubspec.yaml is static \emdash  the Android build number never auto-increments, making releases indistinguishable on-device and on Google Play. No conventional-commit changelog automation, no hotfix branch policy.\par
Top 5 Things to Fix Before Calling It Production-Ready\par
1. Sign the Android APK and Windows installer\par
Unsigned APKs cannot be uploaded to Google Play and are blocked by most enterprise MDMs. The Windows installer will trigger SmartScreen for 100% of users until it accumulates reputation \emdash  or it is EV-signed. Both need signing configured in CI with secrets for the keystore/certificate. This is a hard blocker for real distribution.\par
\par
2. Write integration tests for the SSH state machine\par
The stale-connection bug that triggered this entire session was untested. The reconnect loop, client.done callback, heartbeat, and startShell error path are the most failure-prone code in the app and have zero test coverage. Use mockito or a fake dartssh2 client to test status transitions: connecting \u8594? connected \u8594? transport drop \u8594? reconnecting \u8594? reconnected.\par
\par
3. Raise the PBKDF2 iteration count for backup encryption\par
10,000 iterations of PBKDF2-SHA256 can be cracked at ~2 billion guesses/second on a modern GPU. OWASP 2023 minimum is 600,000. A user who exports a backup and loses control of the file has their entire SSH credential vault exposed with a weak key. Bump to at least 310,000 (NIST minimum) or migrate to Argon2id which is memory-hard.\par
\par
4. Add a global error screen for unhandled exceptions\par
Right now, if an error escapes all local try/catch blocks, Flutter's default red error screen appears in debug mode, or the app silently crashes in release mode. Sentry captures it, but the user sees nothing useful. Add a FlutterError.onError handler and a MaterialApp.builder error boundary that shows a friendly "Something went wrong \emdash  tap to restart" screen in release builds.\par
\par
5. Auto-increment the build number in CI and sync pubspec version to the tag\par
version: 1.0.0+1 in pubspec.yaml is the same for every build. Add a CI step that rewrites pubspec.yaml with the tag version before building: flutter pub version 1.2.3+456. Without this, Android treats all builds as the same version, making in-place upgrades and Play Store submission impossible.\par
\par
Bottom Line\par
Hamma is a genuinely impressive solo/small-team project \emdash  it packs a terminal, SFTP manager, Docker control, systemd, packages, fleet management, and an AI copilot into a single cross-platform Flutter app with a clean architecture, proper credential encryption, and a functioning CI pipeline. That is a lot to get right.\par
\par
What holds it back from a v1.0 label is not feature depth but release engineering fundamentals: unsigned builds that can't be distributed, a 60\'d7 under-powered backup KDF, no test coverage for the SSH core that the whole app depends on, and a static build number. Fix those five items and this is a credible, shippable product.\line\line\line -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------\par
